  In problem solving, the paths towards solutions can be viewed as a sequence
of decisions. The decisions, made by humans or computers, describe a trajectory
through a high-dimensional representation space of the problem. Using
dimensionality reduction, these trajectories can be visualized in lower
dimensional space. Such embedded trajectories have previously been applied to a
wide variety of data, but so far, almost exclusively the self-similarity of
single trajectories has been analyzed. In contrast, we describe patterns
emerging from drawing many trajectories---for different initial conditions, end
states, or solution strategies---in the same embedding space. We argue that
general statements about the problem solving tasks and solving strategies can
be made by interpreting these patterns. We explore and characterize such
patterns in trajectories resulting from human and machine-made decisions in a
variety of application domains: logic puzzles (Rubik's cube), strategy games
